                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.77/117.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-07T19:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 7, 1912—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to Department’s March 30, 11 a.m. Mr. Calero informs me to-day, in a
                    note, that the Government, reflecting the views of the officers of the Mexican
                    National Railways, finds the demands of the American engineers and conductors
                    intolerable and is advised from the same source of the ability of the management
                    to effectively operate the railways without American employees. The note adds
                    the hope of the Government that the American employees and the management will
                    be able to arrive at an understanding and that he has so advised a responsible
                    official.</p>
                <p>I do not share in the optimistic view of the Minister for Foreign Affairs.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
